{"title_page": "Girl Talk (TLC song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Girl Talk\n| cover      = Girl Talk.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[TLC (group)|TLC]]\n| album      = [[3D (TLC album)|3D]]\n| B-side     = Get Away\n| released   = {{Start date|2002|9|6}}\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[maxi single]], [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list |\n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n| writer     = {{flat list |\n*[[Lisa Lopes]]\n*Anita McLoud\n*Edmund Clement\n*[[Kandi Burruss]]\n*[[Tionne Watkins]]}}\n| producer   = Eddie Hustle\n| prev_title = [[What It Ain't (Ghetto Enuff)]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Hands Up (TLC song)|Hands Up]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\n\"'''Girl Talk'''\" is a song by American group [[TLC (group)|TLC]]. It was written by band members [[Lisa Lopes]] and [[Tionne Watkins]] along with Anita McLoud, Edmund \"Eddie Hustle\" Clement, and [[Kandi Burruss]] for the group's fourth studio album, ''[[3D (TLC album)|3D]]'' (2002). Featuring production by Hustle, it was released as the album's lead single in September 2002, along with a previously unreleased song \"Get Away\". While the song contains vocals by Lopes, the music video for \"Girl Talk\" marked the band's first release without Lopes, following her death in April of the same year.\n\nUpon its release, \"Girl Talk\" reached number twenty-three on the US ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart and number twenty-eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=tlc|chart=all}}|title=Artist Chart History \u2013 TLC|publisher=billboard.com|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref> becoming the group's 12th top forty entry on the latter chart. In addition, the song reached the top twenty in Denmark and New Zealand, the top thirty in the UK and the top fifty in Australia. The song appears in the [[Nintendo Gamecube]] and [[Xbox]] game ''[[Freestyle Street Soccer]]''.\n\n==Release==\nThe international maxi singles were released with a B-side track entitled \"Get Away\", written by band member Tionne Watkins and Ray Murray. The song was later featured on the Japanese imported version of \"3D\", and is often praised as a fan favorite.\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] was directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]] and filmed in late October 2002, six months after [[Lisa Lopes]]' death. The video depicts the two remaining members, T-Boz & Chilli, in three different locations; The [[Atlanta|Dirty South]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Africa]], dancing and talking with other girls, representing how girls all over the world \"talk\". An animated segment is used during Left Eye's rap verse, where all three girls appear as cartoon versions of themselves. The video ends with a tribute to Left Eye, reading: \"In Loving Memory of Lisa 'Left Eye' Lopes.\"\n\n==Track listing==\n;European, Australian, South African, and Japanese CD maxi single\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Jacknife Lee Remix) \u2013 3:50\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Kidstuff Vocal Mix) \u2013 7:53\n# \"Get Away\" \u2013 4:14\n\n;UK CD single 1, UK 12\" single\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Jacknife Lee Remix) \u2013 3:50\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Kidstuff Vocal Mix) \u2013 7:53\n\n;UK CD single 2\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Waterfalls\" \u2013 4:36\n# \"No Scrubs\" \u2013 3:39\n\n;European CD single\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Jacknife Lee Remix) \u2013 3:50\n\n;US 12\" single\n:A1. \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n:A2. \"Girl Talk\" (instrumental) \u2013 3:34\n:B1. \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n:B2. \"Girl Talk\" (a cappella) \u2013 3:17\n\n;US DVD single\n# \"Hands Up\" (music video) \u2013 4:01\n# \"Girl Talk\" (music video) \u2013 3:43\n# Photo gallery slideshow \u2013 0:32\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2002) !! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|46|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|5|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2016-11-06}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|14|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2016-11-06}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|13|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/00s/2002/MM-2002-12-21.pdf|title=Euro Chart Hot 100|work=Music & Media|page=11|date=2002-12-21|accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|78\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|79|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|songid=5476|accessdate=2020-03-03}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland3|46|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=November 3,2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Italy|49|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2016-11-06}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|54|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2016-11-06}}\n|-\n|Netherlands ([[Tipparade]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/tipparade/2003/week-1|title=week 1 (4 januari 2003)|language=Dutch|publisher=top40.nl|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|18|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|42|artist=TLC|date=20021208}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|96|artist=TLC|song=Girl Talk|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|30|artist=TLC|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKrandb|9|artist=TLC|date=20021208}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|28|artist=TLC|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|23|artist=TLC|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|21|artist=TLC|accessdate=2013-01-19}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|15|artist=TLC|accessdate=March 24, 2018}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|tlc|girl-talk}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{TLC songs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Talk (Song)}}\n[[Category:2002 singles]]\n[[Category:2002 songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:Arista Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Dave Meyers (director)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lisa Lopes]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kandi Burruss]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tionne Watkins]]\n[[Category:TLC (group) songs]]\n\n[[it:Girl Talk]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Girl Talk\n| cover      = Girl Talk.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[TLC (group)|TLC]]\n| album      = [[3D (TLC album)|3D]]\n| B-side     = Get Away\n| released   = {{Start date|2002|9|6}}\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[maxi single]], [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flat list |\n*[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}}\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n| writer     = {{flat list |\n*[[Lisa Lopes]]\n*Anita McLoud\n*Edmund Clement\n*[[Kandi Burruss]]\n*[[Tionne Watkins]]}}\n| producer   = Eddie Hustle\n| prev_title = [[What It Ain't (Ghetto Enuff)]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Hands Up (TLC song)|Hands Up]]\n| next_year  = 2002\n}}\n\n\"'''Girl Talk'''\" is a song by American group [[TLC (group)|TLC]]. It was written by band members [[Lisa Lopes]] and [[Tionne Watkins]] along with Anita McLoud, Edmund \"Eddie Hustle\" Clement, and [[Kandi Burruss]] for the group's fourth studio album, ''[[3D (TLC album)|3D]]'' (2002). Featuring production by Hustle, it was released as the album's lead single in September 2002, along with a previously unreleased song \"Get Away\". While the song contains vocals by Lopes, the music video for \"Girl Talk\" marked the band's first release without Lopes, following her death in April of the same year.\n\nUpon its release, \"Girl Talk\" reached number twenty-three on the US ''Billboard''{{'}}s Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart and number twenty-eight on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=tlc|chart=all}}|title=Artist Chart History \u2013 TLC|publisher=billboard.com|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref> becoming the group's 12th top forty entry on the latter chart. In addition, the song reached the top twenty in Denmark and New Zealand, the top thirty in the UK and the top fifty in Australia. The song appears in the [[Nintendo Gamecube]] and [[Xbox]] game ''[[Freestyle Street Soccer]]''.\n\n==Release==\nThe international maxi singles were released with a B-side track entitled \"Get Away\", written by band member Tionne Watkins and Ray Murray. The song was later featured on the Japanese imported version of \"3D\", and is often praised as a fan favorite.\n\n==Music video==\nThe [[music video]] was directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]] and filmed in late October 2002, six months after [[Lisa Lopes]]' death. The video depicts the two remaining members, T-Boz & Chilli, in three different locations; The [[Atlanta|Dirty South]], [[Tokyo]] and [[Africa]], dancing and talking with other girls, representing how girls all over the world \"talk\". An animated segment is used during Left Eye's rap verse, where all three girls appear as cartoon versions of themselves. The video ends with a tribute to Left Eye, reading: \"In Loving Memory of Lisa 'Left Eye' Lopes.\"\n\n==Track listing==\n;European, Australian, South African, and Japanese CD maxi single\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Jacknife Lee Remix) \u2013 3:50\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Kidstuff Vocal Mix) \u2013 7:53\n# \"Get Away\" \u2013 4:14\n\n;UK CD single 1, UK 12\" single\n# \"Girl Talk\" (radio mix) \u2013 3:37\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Jacknife Lee Remix) \u2013 3:50\n# \"Girl Talk\" (Kidstuff Vocal Mix) \u2013 7:53\n\n;UK CD single 2\n# \"Girl Talk\